<TEXT>
three tobacco companies in a cigarette 
liability suit will ask again for a mistrial following a judges 
opinion that narrowed the claims against them lawyers said monday 
lawyers for philip morris co liggett group inc and lorillard 
inc will file papers this week for a mistrial in us district 
judge h lee sarokins ruling last thursday said steven c 
parrish a lawyer for morris and lorillard 
the companies have sought at least four mistrials since court 
proceedings began feb 1 and twice have sought to have sarokin 
removed from the case all those efforts were unsuccessful 
sarokin last week dismissed charges brought by antonio cipollone 
on behalf of his wife rose who died of lung cancer at age 58 in 
1984 after four decades of smoking the defendants cigarettes 
cipollone had charged that the companies caused his wifes death by 
failing to market a safer product or do enough research on smoking 
although the judge ruled there was not enough evidence to 
support the claims he decided that the evidence could lead to a 
finding that the companies engaged in conspiracy to cover up the 
dangers of smoking 
the companies say the jury could not decide fairly on the 
remaining contentions because so much evidence on the safer 
cigarette and research issues has been introduced 
sarokin also let stand allegations that liggett failed to warn 
mrs cipollone about the dangers of cigarettes but threw out the 
charge against morris and lorillard because she did not smoke their 
cigarettes after 1966 when congress mandated warnings on cigarette 
packs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

