<TEXT>
twentyseven union members began a 
fast monday as part of the twomonthold strike by thousands of 
construction workers demanding that the government grant wage 
increases and better working conditions 
about 4500 construction workers belonging to four opposition 
labor groups have been on strike since feb 25 
the 27 hunger strikers began their fast at the general workers 
confederation headquarters in managua 
carlos nunez president of the national assembly and the 
sandinista governments representative in talks with domestic 
opposition groups called plans for the hunger strike a political 
publicity show 
the construction workers went on strike after the leftist 
government decreed new wage scales and raised prices for basic 
staples on feb 14 as part of reforms intended to combat inflation 
which reached 1500 percent last year 
government officials have called the strike illegal and labor 
minister benedicto meneses said only 600 workers have walked off 
their jobs 
monday night the labor ministry said negotiations with the 
strikers had been suspended a statement said the unions were 
seeking to return to former payment systems that were eliminated 
precisely because they ran against the logic of the economic reform 
measures 
it called on the strikers to return to work with the guarantee 
they wont be the object of any reprisals 
the strike was called by the general independent workers 
confederation the autonomous workers central of nicaragua the 
confederation of trade union unity and the labor action and unity 
central they claim a membership of 100000 
there was no immediate response from the government to president 
reagans message to congress monday in which he threatened to 
expand the us embargo against nicaragua 
but on sunday president daniel ortega said that if the embargo 
continued the sandinistas would prohibit further shipments from 
the united states of equipment and other assistance to nicaraguan 
organizations 
the embargo had been set to expire april 30 it permits us aid 
and independent donations of supplies to democratic 
organizations including newsprint and equipment for the 
opposition newspaper la prensa 
</TEXT>
