<TEXT>
a lawyer for rock singer mick jagger 
said monday that there was only the barest scintilla of 
evidence that jagger ever heard a song he is accused of pirating 
in his 1985 hit just another night 
a federal court jury got the case monday and deliberated 3 
hours before retiring for the evening 
the jury listened to several tapes and reviewed jaggers travel 
schedule for early 1983 when reggae musician patrick alleys song 
was broadcast in the new york area testimony showed jagger was in 
the area for five days in january and february of that year 
alley is suing jagger maintaining that jagger infringed on his 
copyright of a song with the same name 
two alternate jurors who were dismissed at start of 
deliberations said it seemed to them that jagger had developed his 
song independently 
peter parcher one of jaggers lawyers said the only similarity 
between jaggers song and alleys 1979 song were the title and the 
theme of a man spending one more night with a woman which is 
certainly not original 
parcher said there was only the barest barest scintilla of 
evidence that jagger ever heard alleys song and added that his 
client had no motive to steal patrick alleys song 
alleys attorney thomas farley said alley and jagger had 
several mutual friends and acquaintances and said the songs 
similar choruses were the certain spark that made the songs 
memorable 
if the jury decides jagger infringed upon alleys copyright 
damages would be decided in a second trial unless a settlement were 
reached 
alleys lawyers say jagger netted as much as 6 million from the 
song 
</TEXT>
