<TEXT>
elaines whose clubby confines have provided 
refuge for a generation of creative minds and famous faces 
celebrated its first quartercentury monday with a celebrity bash 
elaine kaufman the rotund proprietress who rewards loyalty and 
fame with choice tables expected her nice neighborhood 
restaurant to be filled with people whose names have filled 
gossip columns for years 
for the party the checkedclothcovered tables were removed 
the ceiling was filled with balloons and rotating spotlights were 
set up outside 
a crowd of onlookers watched as celebrities filed by george 
segal sidney lumet pat kennedy lawford peter maas eli wallach 
iman connie chung raquel welch billy dee williams cheryl tiegs 
halston terry southern jerzy kosinski 
the eighth avenue subway at rush hour is a picnic compared to 
this said jackie mason in the jampacked interior 
these people are used to being treated like kings here 
tonight they are treated like cockroaches 
and this was early by elaines standards 10 pm 
this place is a living people magazine said bartender brian 
mcdonald 
but a glitzy night of revelry is hardly what the regulars think 
of when they think of elaines 
a comfortable tavern chockablock with posters photos and book 
covers donated by its celebrated clientele elaines has evolved 
from a writers and artists hangout to a required stop in the 
citys seeandbeseen circuit 
saturday night was typical woody allen albert finney and 
paloma picasso among others prince was there a couple of weeks 
ago 
allen opened his cinematic valentine to new york manhattan 
with a scene set in elaines hes a regular elaine said because 
he loves to peoplewatch its comfortable nobody bothers him 
we make him what he wants 
the food critics love to point out is undistinguished its 
the restaurant where you get the least for your money 
according to the zagat restaurant survey 
and its reputation deserved or not is that service can be rude 
and inattentive if youve never made the bestseller list even 
writer george plimpton among the most loyal of regulars said 
im afraid you dont get treated very well if you dont have a 
pencil in your top pocket 
nevertheless it usually fills up by 9 pm with stars 
stargazers yuppies and just neighborhood folks those at the bar 
can nurse 350 beers and watch the scene 
in a city where formality sometimes chokes the fun out of a 
meal elaines is a relaxing familiar retreat its regulars say 
it offers an ambience of camaraderie that is centered on 
elaine herself shes the den mother there said author gay 
talese adding its like a boarding house youve got the round 
table and you dont need a reservation if youre a friend of 
hers 
if youre not youll sit farther back 
detractors and celebritywatchers alike make too big a deal out 
of the place elaine said 
i think a lot of people just come in to have dinner she 
said and you have a good time a good bottle of wine a nice 
plate of pasta i mean thats life 
when she plunked down 10000 for the bar in 1963 she already 
knew some show folk writers and artists from her days as a 
waitress and cafe manager in greenwich village 
actually what i did was just bring the village uptown she 
said 
then it was barely going a rather sleepy place up there 
plimpton recalled friends got their friends to go it was just 
one room very quiet and we would play darts 
elaine made sure it was a very informal nonfrantic 
atmosphere now its a bit different and more expensive 
overall however its much the same as it was 25 years ago 
said elaine regulars can count on a good table and count on her 
being there 
im not changing it all the time she said im not going 
with the current trend 
