<TEXT>
a group of panamanian dissidents is planning 
to undertake a military operation against strongman manuel antonio 
noriega by the beginning of next week an opposition leader said 
monday 
ambassador juan b sosa who has maintained his loyalty to 
ousted president eric arturo delvalle told reporters the group is 
made up of very knowledgeable officers who have many friends in the 
panamanian defense forces or pdf 
sosa gave no details but the group apparently is comprised of 
highranking defectors from the defense forces who came to the 
united states shortly after panamas crisis erupted two months ago 
with delvalles ouster 
one is air force lt col augusto villalaz who has been living 
in exile in washington for the past five weeks he claimed that he 
and other defense force pilots flew more than 90000 pounds of 
weapons from cuba to panama before he defected 
sosa who has refused to relinquish the embassy to a replacement 
envoy appointed by the new government in panama said the dissident 
group has set up a military command and has intimate 
knowledge of the defense forces 
we are very confident that the military actions will have the 
help the support of people within the pdf sosa said this is 
an asset we never had before 
a military coup attempt against noriega last month was put down 
quickly 
asked why he was disclosing a planned military operation at a 
news conference sosa said noriega is aware that his opponents will 
not give up the struggle against him he indicated that he did not 
believe that the disclosure would hurt the chances for the success 
of the plan 
sosa said the plan is being worked out on the assumption that no 
assistance from the united states or other outside countries will 
be necessary 
us officials have said for weeks that opposition to noriega in 
the defense forces has been growing but that the dissident elements 
have been unable to agree on a plan for his ouster 
the reagan administration has imposed a series of economic and 
diplomatic sanctions against panama over the past two months and 
officials have become increasingly frustrated over noriegas 
ability to survive these pressures 
the new york times quoted an unidentified reagan administration 
official as saying that us economic sanctions against panama 
would be relaxed within a week or so 
the official said the treasury department was considering a list 
of possible exemptions including payment of utility bills and 
normal administrative fees and costs such as gasoline excise 
taxes rental fees and airline landing fees the times reported in 
its tuesday editions 
noriega is under indictment in the united states on drug 
smuggling charges 
some in the administration favor a us military move against 
panama but several proposals which have been passed on to the 
pentagon have been given a hostile reception 
sosa said that among the seven new cabinet officers appointed on 
sunday by delvalles successor president manuel solis palma were 
several with procuban leanings 
at the state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said the 
united states does not view the solis palma government as 
legitimate and she therefore declined comment on the reshuffling 
asked about the shutoff sunday of electricity to a us embassy 
annex in panama mrs oakley said the state department does not 
believe embassy operations will be affected 
the electricity to the annex and to the apartments of at least 
45 embassy workers was cut off because of nonpayment of bills 
as part of an attempt to deprive panamanian authorities of cash 
the administration has ordered a ban on all payments to the 
government by us citizens and organizations 
