<TEXT>
soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev is facing 
serious obstacles in his effort to overhaul the troubled 
inefficient soviet economy and things arent likely to improve 
anytime soon according to us intelligence agencies 
gorbachevs ambitious program to create a modern more dynamic 
soviet economy ran into trouble in 1987 says a joint study by 
the central intelligence agency and the defense intelligence agency 
the shortterm outlook for gorbachevs economic program is not 
good concluded the study which was released sunday by the 
congressional joint economic committee 
the real loser in 1987 appeared to be the consumer who now 
three years into gorbachevs economic program has seen almost no 
increase in his standard of living the study said 
the main problems last year were poor weather and resistance to 
change in the huge slowmoving soviet bureaucracy said the report 
as a result the soviet gross national product grew only 05 
percent last year compared with a 39 percent increase in 1986 
which was the first full year of gorbachevs term 
the gross national product is the total value of all goods and 
services produced and is a key measure of an economy 
by contrast the us gnp grew by 29 percent in both 1986 and 
1987 but the american economy is much larger and exact comparisons 
are difficult to make 
sen william proxmire dwis chairman of the joint economic 
committee said the study shows the soviet economy did not pause 
last year it stumbled this does not mean that the reform program 
is necessarily doomed or that gorbachev will be ousted 
it is still too soon to pass judgment on the reforms or on 
gorbachevs leadership proxmire said 
the study predicted that unless gorbachev can turn things 
around he faces trouble 
tension within society and the leadership will increase it 
said bureaucrats will become increasingly frustrated by loss of 
privileges and status and by demands that they show greater 
initiative military leaders are likely to become more and more 
uneasy if benefits from the industrial modernization fail to 
materialize 
soviet citizens will need to see some improvement in living 
standards if the regime is to achieve necessary gains in worker 
productivity and avoid widespread discontent the study said 
failure to head off these tensions would at a minimum make 
it more difficult to pursue his economic program vigorously and 
could ultimately call into question his strong political position 
at home the study said 
the study was presented april 13 the joint economic committee 
released a declassified version 
when gorbachev took over in march 1985 the study noted he 
inherited an aging backward extremely inefficient economy he 
made reform a top priority 
last years problems were caused by a combination of factors 
the study said 
familiar problems with poor weather and transportation 
bottlenecks were compounded by the disruptions caused by the 
introduction of economic reforms it said 
agricultural output fell because of bad weather industrial 
quality control measures also proved to be particularly 
disruptive especially early in the year thus industry only 
grew 15 percent and the civilian machinebuilding sector didnt 
grow at all 
