<TEXT>
kiev residents who get a mysterious ache or pain 
are apt to grasp for the easy explanation radiation from 
chernobyl 
such is one of the lingering scars of the worlds worst nuclear 
accident a fear of what longterm health problems will result from 
the explosion and fire two years ago at the chernobyl nuclear 
plant 80 miles north of kiev the ukrainian capital 
a kiev resident speaking during a moscow visit on condition of 
anonymity said some people blame everything from headaches to 
toothaches on radiation from chernobyl this is despite the 
governments repeated assurances that radiation levels in the 
region are normal and safe 
doctors in accidentaffected regions are spending most of their 
time combating radiophobia the government newspaper izvestia 
reported in february 
a soviet pediatrician said last august that more than 2000 
healthy children were born to mothers who lived around chernobyl 
during the april 26 1986 disaster which killed 31 people and 
spewed a cloud of radioactivity worldwide 
but an american doctor who treated some chernobyl victims 
robert gale wrote april 1 in pravda that the accidents longterm 
effects cannot be predicted he guessed that problems could include 
birth defects genetic deviations and an additional 6000 cancer 
victims in the next 50 to 70 years 
although a pravda report on sunday criticized nepotism 
drunkenness and sloppy repairs at the plant other reports marking 
the disasters second anniversary portray life returning to normal 
they say chernobyls reactors are generating electricity again 
and people are living nearby in once dangerously radioactive areas 
but the fear of nuclear power remains 
taking advantage of soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs 
campaign for glasnost or more openness on some issues nuclear 
power opponents have been speaking out and in some cases halting 
construction of new nuclear plants 
who will say that each of these atomic power stations built 
or planned does not conceal another potential chernobyl 
ukrainian writer oles honchar asked at a conference last october 
the governments answer one can say now with confidence that 
even a recurrence of the errors which were made in chernobyl would 
not lead to such a disaster nuclear power minister nikolai 
lukonin told the soviet news agency tass last week 
officials say the publics fears are unjustified plans call for 
doubling by 1990 the amount of electricity generated by nuclear 
plants from the 1985 level of 28 million kilowatts 
part of the increased production is from the chernobyl plant 
itself 
but the resumed production reportedly is not without its costs 
v lukyanenko the communist party head in slavutich a new town 
for plant workers 35 miles from chernobyl said last december that 
sloppy work poor discipline and safety violations at the plant 
contributed to 36 accidents over a 10month period three of them 
fatal 
yuri k semyonov deputy head of the chernobyl cleanup 
commission denied at a news conference last week that any major 
accident had occurred at the plant since the 1986 explosion 
last july three officials in charge of the plant during the 
accident were convicted of gross negligence and sentenced to 10 
years in a labor camp the government blamed the accident on human 
error in shutting down safety systems to conduct unauthorized 
experiments 
in january the ruling politburo put the accidents cost at 
138 billion 
another price paid was in peoples shaken faith in the 
governments ability to harness nuclear energy safely the 
newspaper komsomolskaya pravda said nuclear plants once lent 
prestige to a city but that was before chernobyl 
popular opposition has prevented building two nuclear plants 
near the ukrainian city of odessa and the byelorussian capital of 
minsk 
construction of a nuclear plant in the russian city of krasnodar 
was halted because residents complained it was in an 
earthquakeprone area and too close to a nature preserve 
public complaints appear to have been at least partly behind the 
governments may 1987 decision to stop building two additional 
reactors at chernobyl 
thirty ukrainian scientists writing jan 21 in the newspaper 
literaturnaya ukraina criticized on ecological grounds the 
governments plans to add reactors to three other plants they 
accused the government of ignoring the bitter lessons of 
chernobyl 
