<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
giving federal prison wardens more power to decide what 
publications inmates may read 
the court said it will review a ruling that limits the authority 
of officials to censor reading material behind prison bars 
one of the prisoners in the case is jack henry abbott a 
convicted murderer and bank robber who achieved notoriety after he 
was befriended by norman mailer and other prominent writers and 
editors 
six weeks after abbott was freed in a workrelease program in 
1981 he stabbed to death an aspiring actor outside of a new york 
city restaurant where the victim was working as a waiter abbotts 
book on prison life in the belly of the beast was critically 
acclaimed 
abbott is among prisoners who challenged federal regulations 
restricting publications that may be sent to inmates 
the us circuit court of appeals here ruled last july that the 
rules go too far in giving wardens control over what publications 
inmates may subscribe to or receive 
the appeals court ordered further trial court hearings where 
officials will have to prove that 46 publications should be banned 
because they threaten security order or rehabilitation 
the freeexpression rights of inmates require that officials 
shoulder the burden of proof when they seek to ban publications 
the appeals court said 
among the publications officials tried to ban were for example 
an issue of the call a leftwing newspaper that included an 
article charging inhumane treatment by racist guards in 
federal prisons 
officials at a federal penitentiary in atlanta said the article 
is considered not to be in the best interest of discipline good 
order and security 
but the appeals court said that is an insufficient reason to ban 
the publication the officials failed to prove the material 
encouraged conduct which would constitute or otherwise was likely 
to produce a breach of security or order or an impairment of 
rehabilitation 
the same limits on official power should apply to sexually 
explicit material the appeals court said 
also the appeals court said censoring parts of a publication is 
less restrictive than banning the newspaper or magazine entirely 
rejecting an entire publication where a part is objectionable is 
inconsistent with the first amendment the appeals court said 
the constitutions first amendment ensures freedom of speech 
the reagan administration urged the supreme court to restore 
fully the prison regulations 
while a warden may have a legitimate fear that a particular 
publication will cause problems he will rarely be able to prove a 
likelihood of violence or disorder as a result of the admission of 
a publication justice department lawyers said 
they cited uprisings last year by inmates from cuba in two us 
prisons as evidence that information from the outside can in 
some circumstances have grave consequences within a prison 
the government also argued that the number of publications 
excluded is small 
between sept 1 1986 and aug 31 1987 some 1728 publications 
were withheld out of 18 million sent to federal inmates the 
governments appeal said 
the groups challenging the prison regulations are the prisoners 
union weekly guardian associates and the revolutionary socialist 
league 
the case is meese vs abbott 871344 
</TEXT>
