<TEXT>
the supreme court today turned away a case in 
which missouri officials were found guilty of sex discrimination by 
not hiring enough women as highway maintenance workers 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by state 
officials who said lower courts improperly weighed the evidence 
the justices also refused to hear an appeal by women who said 
remedies ordered by the lower courts were inadequate 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals last september said there 
was adequate evidence for a federal jury to find that the missouri 
highway and transportation commission discriminated against women 
in the states eighth district 
the verdict was based partly on anecdotal evidence and partly on 
statistics that showed the number of women maintenance workers in 
the district was a small fraction of the women in the regional work 
force 
the appeals court said that from jan 1 1975 through may 31 
1980 the state hired eight women as maintenance workers and 89 men 
for those jobs 
during that period women comprised up to 48 percent of the work 
force the appeals court noted 
missouri officials interpreted the statistics differently they 
said only 312 women applied for maintenance work compared to 3566 
men during that period the state said it hired 26 percent of the 
female applicants and 25 percent of the men who applied 
but the 8th circuit court said the equal hiring rate did not 
prove the state was innocent of bias 
a judge and jury were free to weigh the inference of 
nondiscrimination arising from the hiring rate against the 
inference of discrimination arising from the anecdotal and 
statistical evidence the appeals court said it added the 
evidence was sufficient to support a verdict that the state 
engaged in a pattern or practice of discrimination against 
women 
the appeals court upheld a ruling that some 150 women may share 
in back pay to be awarded by the state the group is made up of 
women who were qualified to be hired as maintenance workers if the 
state had not discriminated on the basis of sex 
but the appeals court overturned a portion of a federal judges 
ruling that missouri hire from 37 percent to 48 percent women for 
future maintenance worker openings 
the 8th circuit court ordered the hiring goal replaced by a 
generalized injunction prohibitng further discrimination against 
women 
the appeals court also refused to order the state to hire four 
women who were among the first to charge the state with 
discrimination and it declined to extend its ruling beyond the 
eighth district to make it statewide 
the mountain states legal foundation a conservative group and 
officials from wisconsin and wyoming said the finding of 
discrimination against missouri could have farreaching 
consequences 
they said the charges were based on questionable statistical 
evidence the eligible work force consisted of all working women 
between ages 18 and 70 who had drivers licenses and an eighth 
grade education they noted 
this labor pool is too broad because it failed to consider 
only those individuals willing and able to do the work in 
question they said 
the cases are missouri highway commission vs catlett 871415 
and catlett vs missouri highway commission 871416 
</TEXT>
