<TEXT>
british airways will ban smoking on one of its 
busiest domestic routes for a month beginning tuesday in the first 
of a series of smokefree flights 
the airline will forbid an estimated 2500 passengers from 
lighting up on its 12 daily onehour shuttle flights between 
londons heathrow airport and glasgow scotland 
on june 6 some british airways flights to the continent will 
become smokefree for a month and in november some los angeles and 
new yorkbound flights join the experiment 
several small british carriers have banned smoking on domestic 
and international flights but british airways is the largest to 
try it the companys only domestic competitor british midland 
airways said it had no plans to ban smoking 
unlike the united states where the government forced airlines 
to ban smoking on all domestic flights shorter than two hours 
britain has no national laws concerning smoking about 34 percent 
of british adults smoke cigarettes 
british airways officials said they took action because research 
showed that if smoking were banned the number of customers who 
would fly more often was four times the number who would switch 
airlines 
in recent years demand for nonsmoking areas on our aircraft 
have grown and grown today on most routes smokers are very much in 
the minority said jim harris marketing director for the 
airline we have steadily increased nonsmoking areas to reflect 
this trend now we want a full trial of customer reaction to 
see if we can extend the idea still further 
airline spokesman michael blunt said the carrier will decide 
whether to continue the bans after studying surveys and other 
passenger response 
stephen eyres director of a prosmoking group criticized the 
idea as discriminatory dangerous and unnecessary 
our view is that so long as nonsmokers wishes are respected 
with definite nosmoking areas there also ought to be areas where 
smokers can light up and not be treated like social lepers he 
said 
he said the bans would lead to safety risks from people smoking 
in toilets and said that it was unnecessary because cabin air is 
changed every three minutes 
opposition lawmaker george foulkes said monday he would 
introduce a bill in parliament tuesday to ban smoking in the 
workplace saying some people regard it as torture to have to 
work in a smokefilled workplace 
but opposition legislation rarely passes the legislative body 
and a government spokesman said that government planned no national 
laws banning smoking on airlines or in public places 
its like drinking its a question of choice its a part of 
societys freedoms said paul hayward of the department of health 
and social services at this moment this government has no 
intention to inhibit this generally accepted freedom 
</TEXT>
