<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday let stand an 
arizona telephone companys ban on sexually explicit dialup 
message services 
in the first dialaporn case to reach the high court the 
justices without comment declined to hear arguments that mountain 
bells refusal to carry sexually explicit message services violates 
freespeech rights 
the courts action came a week after congress sent to president 
reagan a bill that would ban all dialaporn services which are 
available to callers through 976 exchanges and atampts 900 
longdistance lines 
state governments also have been working to limit availability 
of dialaporn services and last week the federal communications 
commission fined two california dialaporn companies 600000 each 
for allegedly failing to prevent children from hearing their 
messages 
the supreme courts action clearly puts the ball in the phone 
companies court said bradley keirnes vice president of 
citizens for decency through law inc a phoenix arizbased 
public interest law firm specializing in obscenity law 
keirnes said phone companies now have a green light to pull 
the plug on dialaporn services without fear of violating the 
companies first amendment rights 
rep thomas j bliley jr rva who spearheaded the move in 
the house to approve a dialaporn ban said the courts action 
bolsters his belief that such a ban will withstand a court test 
it indicates the thinking of the court which is that this 
kind of speech is not protected by the first amendment he said 
mountain bell a us west company was pleased with the decision 
but the parent company is not considering extending the arizona ban 
to the 13 other states in its territory a spokesman said 
in arizona dialaporn services were particularly harmful to 
our reputation so we felt that a ban was the most appropriate 
action for arizona but there are different circumstances in 
different states said us west spokesman blair johnson 
in its other states us west is offering customers onetime 
free blocking of 976 services establishing a separate prefix for 
dialaporn services and is no longer billing or collecting for 
these services 
we think those will be effective and give parents a tool to 
keep children from gaining access to these types of services 
johnson said 
pacific bell spokeswoman sandy hale said her company will 
review our position in light of the supreme courts action to see 
if there are direct implications 
other bell companies and american telephone amp telegraph co had 
no comment on the supreme court action 
mountain bell in 1985 banned from its 976 network all businesses 
that provide adult entertainment messages with sexually oriented 
content 
the policy was challenged by carlin communications inc and 
sapphire communications inc as impeding their freedom of speech 
only the government or some agent of the government can violate 
someones constitutional rights so the two companies argued that 
mountain bells policy represented a state action 
they said that because mountain bell is a heavily regulated 
public utility that had been pressured by state authorities to pull 
the plug on dialaporn services the companys action amounted to 
an action of the state 
a federal trial judge ruled that mountain bell could not refuse 
to carry the dialaporn messages but the 9th us circuit court 
of appeals reversed that ruling last year saying mountain bells 
action did not amount to a state action 
new york attorney lawrence abelman representing carlin did not 
return a telephone call for comment sapphire is a subsidiary of 
carlin 
a similar decision by another federal appeals court previously 
enabled southern bell to rid its 976 networks of dialaporn 
services in florida georgia north carolina and south carolina 
