talks last week that included discussion of a moratorium on fishing 
in the bering seas socalled doughnut hole 
while no agreement was reached between the united states and the 
soviet union over the future of fishing in the doughnut hole 
another round of meetings is expected in moscow later this spring 
wolfe earlier had said the ussoviet negotiations were 
exploratory and involved a good exchange of views 
both countries are concerned that overfishing in the doughnut 
hole by foreign trawlers including those from japan south 
korea china and poland could cause a decline in the catch in the 
us and soviet fishing zones that surround the area 
the 4500square mile doughnut hole is considered one of the 
richest fishing grounds in the world and the catch in the area has 
grown from about 200000 metric tons to more than 1 million metric 
tons over the past four years 
both the soviets and the us would prefer a voluntary ban on 
fishing in the doughnut hole the moratorium could be temporary 
or permanent as scientists study the fish stocks in the bering sea 
