four of the navys main nonnuclear missiles 
still are having quality problems that have delayed delivery or 
produced some substandard weapons the general accounting office 
said monday 
all of the missile systems we examined had defects that is 
they failed in one respect or another to conform with contract 
specifications said the congressional watchdog agency 
the gao reviewed the phoenix highspeed antiradiation harm 
harpoon and sparrow missiles four weapons deployed on a variety 
of navy ships for use against other ships and planes 
the review done for the house energy and commerce 
investigations subcommittee found 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
design and workmanship problems on safety and arming devices 
aboard the phoenix aim54c problems which the gao said have 
delayed deliveries of more than 500 phoenix missiles the weapon is 
built by hughes aircraft of tucson ariz 
pressure transducers for some harms may not have been tested 
before being put into the missiles the transducer is used in 
activating the weapons targetseeking device the chief contractor 
is texas instruments 
altimeters for the harpoon were being accepted under a contract 
deviation permitting a solderingrelated condition which the gao 
said could affect the weapons reliability the main contractor is 
mcdonnelldouglas 
detonators on some sparrows were unknowingly built without 
enough explosive compound to set off the warhead the chief 
contractor is raytheon 
most of the problems occurred at the level of subcontractors 
the gao said 
one common problem was that changes were made in manufacturing 
processes which were unknown to the prime contractor but affected 
the quality of the product the gao told congress 
many of the problems related to soldering but it is unclear how 
serious the problems are the gao said 
some contractors and government officials believe that certain 
requirements in the navys soldering specification are more 
stringent than necessary to have a reliable missile the report 
said 
they cite high reliability rates and the successful use of 
missiles that deviate from the soldering specifications as evidence 
that the navys soldering specifications may be too stringent it 
said 
the pentagon in a response that was part of the review said it 
partially agrees with the gao 
jack katzen deputy assistant secretary of defense for systems 
said the pentagon acknowledges that a number of problems have 
been experienced during the production of navy missiles 
but katzen added contrary to the gao implication in no case 
has the navy knowingly accepted missiles suspected of containing 
defects that could affect the performance of the missile in any 
case where the defects were determined to affect performance the 
contractor was required to take the necessary corrective actions 
in addition the gao noted pilots ordnance officers and other 
navy officials aboard ships were satisfied with the missiles 
performance and capabilities and cited no particular problems 
