lanny ross an actor and singer whose smooth 
classically trained tenor made him one of the most popular stars of 
radios golden era died monday he was 82 
ross died of heart failure at lenox hill hospital where he had 
been admitted after two recent strokes family members said 
ross whose theme song was moonlight and roses was a 
familar radio star on several shows in the 1930s and 1940s 
including showboat he was known as the troubadour of the 
moon on hit parade 
he appeared in several movies in the 1930s including melody 
in spring college rhythm the lady objects and 
gullivers travels 
ross appeared with irving berlin and bob hope in shows overseas 
during world war ii then starred in some of the early television 
shows of the late 1940s 
he later had a daily show on wcbs in new york featuring 
conversation recordings and his own singing 
he retired from regular appearances in the early 1970s but 
continued doing occasional shows including a tour in 1980 with 
harry james called the big broadcast of 1937 
ross who was born in seattle but grew up in new york city was 
a sprinter who was selected for the 1928 olympic team but chose 
instead to tour europe as leader and soloist of the yale glee club 
he was schooled at the juilliard school and obtained a law 
degree from columbia university but again he stayed with singing 
ross was married in 1935 to the former olive white who died in 
1984 he is survived by his brother who lives in montrose pa 
a memorial service was scheduled for may 13 at st bartholomews 
church 
