<TEXT>
there wont be any elephants but there will be a 
cast of 600 performing for an arena seating 15000 people in this 
summers aida extravaganza at earls hall 
it is the largest opera setting ever in britain the cavernous 
hall also used for ice shows and pop concerts covers 12 acres and 
was the largest reinforced concrete building in europe when it was 
built in 1937 
its seating capacity is six times greater than the royal opera 
house in covent garden and ticket prices at 40 and 4750 are 
about half the price of good seats at the opera house 
public fascination with giuseppe verdis opera first performed 
in cairo in 1871 abounds 
the tickets are going so well that we have extended the run 
from six nights to seven said lilian hochhauser who with her 
husband victor heads one of three groups of impresarios who got 
together to stage aida at earls court near kensington in west 
london 
the triumphal procession in aida has included elephants in 
some productions but animals were turned down for earls court 
elephants in egypt are totally historically inaccurate and 
camels were not originally known there either mrs hochhauser 
said everybody wants animals but i think perhaps its better not 
to start 
asked about a newspaper report that the impresarios expect a 2 
million profit she said nothing like that and you can say i 
laughed hysterically 
she also declined to say how much the production would cost 
we dont know what to expect because production costs have 
risen so enormously this is unknown territory theres never been 
an opera at earls court before and never one in britain on this 
scale she said 
i think there are thousands of people who are intrigued by 
opera and would like to hear one but they are put off by the price 
and the lowercost seats always sell out quickly 
they feel an opera house is not their world but they would 
feel more at home in a place like earls court she said 
mrs hochhauser said the royal opera and its rival the english 
national opera toyed over the years with the idea of going to 
earls court 
but they never came up with a solution to the set problem 
they didnt have one to fit she said 
american mezzosoprano grace bumbry will portray aida on opening 
night and give one extra performance while other international 
stars will rotate in the leading roles 
