<TEXT>
concerned that some military men 
might still be restless in the barracks argentinas civilian 
government is running television spots to promote democracy 
democracy comes from a greek word meaning peoples choice 
the narrator says solemnly in one of them 
the commercials follow revolts at three army camps last year and 
similar uprisings three months ago at six army garrisons by the 
cashiered rebel leader lt col aldo rico 
the military which has a history of intervention in government 
turned government over to civilians in 1983 after ruling for seven 
years 
president raul alfonsins radical civic union party and the 
opposition peronist party have began debate on a law to amend the 
constitution to strengthen civilian rule and reform the military to 
keep the armed forces out of politics 
this country is tired of the continous agitations provoked by 
a small group that does not represent the general sentiment in the 
armed forces said antonio cafiero the governor of buenos aires 
province chairman of the peronist party and a leading 
presidential candidate 
no civilian president in argentina has completed a full term in 
60 years the military has toppled governments here six times since 
1930 most recently when isabel peron was ousted in 1976 as the 
successor to her husband president juan d peron 
alfonsin has 20 months left in his sixyear term 
but recent events indicate domestic instability recent 
terrorist bombings in this capital and cordoba wounded four people 
including two federal policemen one terrorist suspect was killed 
by police 
prorico graffiti has spread from shantytowns outside buenos 
aires to downtown near the seat of government 
rico is a patriot rico is god and rico is freedom 
the graffiti says 
rico is being held pending rebellion charges in the magdalena 
military prison 62 miles south of buenos aires the prison is where 
five former military leaders including two military expresidents 
also are held 
the five leaders of the former military junta were convicted by 
the alfonsin government for their roles in human rights abuses 
during argentinas dirty war a campaign waged in the late 
1970s by the military against alleged leftist subversion 
at least 9000 civilians vanished without a trace according to 
a government panel but human rights groups say the number of 
people abducted tortured and ultimately disappeared is closer 
to 30000 
a year ago flashing tv spots saying democracy or 
dictatorship urged civilians to take to the streets to show 
support of the government during military uprisings april 1521 in 
buenos aires cordoba and tucuman 
alfonsin won the surrender of rico at campo de mayo argentinas 
largest army base in suburban buenos aires and told 400000 people 
assembled in the central plaza de mayo the house is in order and 
no blood was shed 
when new rebel uprisings in january ended after 96 hours with 
ricos surrender again alfonsin said we have again put our 
house in order 
but in the past year conditions have worsened on the economic 
and social fronts 
argentina had to renegotiate its 543 billion foreign debt 
thirdlargest in latin america and inflation has run at a rate of 
206 percent in the 12month period workers are restive because 
their wages buy less and less and alfonsins party was routed in 
congressional and gubernatorial elections by the resurgent 
peronists 
human rights groups such as the mothers of the plaza de mayo 
made up of relatives who lost loved ones in the dirty war 
charged alfonsin caved in to rico and that he pushed a law through 
congress that pardoned most officers accused of rights atrocities 
rico meanwhile has attracted support from rightist groups such 
as national alert an organization that favors a return to military 
rule 
three army officers have gone underground since february 
announcing they sided with rico and planned to fight what they 
described as the marxist enemy 
rico maintains the military should not be penalized for tactics 
he described as necessary in its 1970s war against subversion or be 
blamed for the embarrassing loss to britain in the 1982 falklands 
war 
while rico has found support among younger midlevel army 
officers he is the butt of many local jokes particularly about 
his surrendering after vowing to fight to the finish 
argentines say rico has broken an unofficial record by 
surrendering three times in six years first during the falklands 
war where he was a decorated commando and twice at his own 
rebellions 
