<TEXT>
eric hansen has vivid memories of the split second 
it took to make the decision turn his back on civilization and 
return to the borneo jungle he had just spent five months crossing 
on foot 
six years after his marathon trip other memories continue to 
haunt hansen who relates his experiences in his new book 
stranger in the forest on foot across borneo houghton 
mifflin co 1795 
he recalls his brush with death with former headhunters 
convinced he was an evil spirit and his fantasies about 
crosscountry skiing while trudging through the hot leech and 
insectinfested rain forest 
departing from kuching in the west in may 1982 hansen made a 
2500mile journey through uncharted rain forest to tanjungselor in 
the east and back carrying only a bed sheet a change of clothes 
and barter goods 
he had the company of guides for much of the time but also 
traveled alone he emerged a changed man a spearwielding hunter 
and a gatherer whose western sense of time had washed away 
after spending five months in the jungle i wasnt fully aware 
of how much i had changed hansen said then i went back two 
more months and i had changed even more 
in singapore his first real exposure to civilization 
afterwards there was all this traffic and the pollution and 
i was acutely aware of the fact that there were no trees at all 
and i felt much more uncomfortable coming back into western society 
than i had going into the jungle 
civilization lost its terrors within about two months for the 
author but longterm changes remain to this day 
im much more patient much more resilient its very much 
developed my selfconfidence he said in a recent interview 
the borneo journey was not the first adventure for the 
40yearold los angeles native who has traveled to nepal and 
northern afghanistan he also has worked as a goldsmith a buffalo 
catcher and as a barber for mother teresas home for the destitute 
in calcutta 
like his other experiences hansen said that the decision to 
embark on a rain forest odyssey was compulsive 
i think a lot of us fantasized about a place we want to go or 
a situation we would like to be in and most of us are quite happy 
to keep it on that fantasy level he said i thought about 
going to borneo for five or six years and it became an overwhelming 
desire on my part 
hansens 278page book is at its most fascinating when it 
juxtaposes civilization against the rain forest and its creatures 
the author among them among such vignettes is an episode 
describing the aftermath of a wild boar hunt with parangs heavy 
knives 
squatting on my haunches i could feel the fat running down my 
forearms and dripping from my elbows i was totally absorbed in the 
meal when i heard a vaguely familiar droning sound growing louder 
and louder 
i looked up through a gap in the jungle canopy and saw for 
perhaps five seconds a commercial airliner 
i imagined myself sitting on the plane far below at the 
edge of a small clearing almost hidden from sight i could see 
myself seated by a campfire with two brownskinned jungle men 
speaking an unknown language nearby lay the steaming carcass of a 
wild boar 
from that perspective i suddenly realized what an astonishing 
situation i was in submerged in a sea of giant trees hunting wild 
animals a bloodied parang at my waist the stuff of pure fantasy 
six months earlier 
hansens encounter with american missionaries and his decision 
to retrace his steps is perhaps the keystone episode and clearly 
explains the triteness of civilization to a man grown 
accustomed to harsher realities 
ian and julie were perched nervously on the edge of their 
seats staring at me perhaps waiting for me to disappear i looked 
at the christian paintings calendars and framed scriptural quotes 
that covered the walls i had been in the jungle too long to make 
any sense of them 
all these symbols seemed trite and out of place and their 
puppy that sweetsmelling freshly shampooed little bundle of 
white fluff would have been torn to pieces in thirty seconds by the 
village hunting dogs 
hansen chuckled as he thought back to that time 
they had this little bungalow beside the jungle and inside the 
house was a perfect time capsule he said everything about it 
was ridiculous from the soap to the rugs to the cookies in a jar 
i was convinced that it had been brought by helicopter and just 
dropped there 
in the book he presents the forest and its inhabitants at their 
most frightening on his return trip when he ignored the locals 
advice and embarks alone during the season of fear the former 
time for headhunting when evil spirits lurk 
hansen was mistaken for a bali saleng half man half 
spirit who kills for blood and who cannot be killed 
what i did not know was that the description of bali saleng 
changed regularly he writes at the time the description 
was a tall whiteskinned man with brownish hair who walks by 
himself in the jungle 
his book describes several close calls with frightened natives 
including one hairraising encounter where he was stripped and 
crossexamined for hours until he laboriously convinced his 
interrogators to let him free 
hansen said his journey left him none the worse for wear and 
that he is looking forward to his next project an extended tour 
of rugged north yemen 
the slightly built balding adventurer laughed heartily when 
told that he did not seem physically rugged enough for such 
experiences 
i think theres a myth fed by movies and television that its 
the hairychested gunslinging whipwielding individual that 
conquers the mountain or the river or the woman or whatever he 
said 
in fact ive never seen anyone in real life like that get 
very far because theyre the first ones to get sick or 
complain or freak out when something happens 
when they cant scream or pay somebody off they give up 
</TEXT>
