<TEXT>
interstate 95 the 1866mile corridor 
that takes truckers snowbirds and salesmen from maine to florida 
begins at the canadian border in this far north potato town 
before reaching bangor the nearest big city i95 winds through 
miles of potato farms brushes the haynesville woods made famous 
by dick curless country and western hit tombstone every mile 
then passes through a strand of white birches before cutting 
through the brooding argyle peat bog 
remote and isolated the only access to points south before the 
opening of the twolane highway in 1966 were state routes 2 and 2a 
hilly winding treacherous roads particularly in winter then 
the trip to bangor could take up to four hours and had to be a 
wellplanned event 
we would go only a couple times a year recalls lois ward 
62 who has lived her entire life in this aroostook county 
shiretown of 6750 wed leave early in the morning do our 
shopping have dinner and it was probably 10 oclock at night 
before we were home it was an all day thing but it was grand 
fun 
today the interstate is a fourlane highway and the speed limit 
65 mph which has cut the driving time to bangor in half 
it was a godsend as far as getting to the southern part of the 
state lifelong area resident robert anderson 50 said of the 
highway the interstate cant be equalled in my opinion 
anywhere 
the opening of the interstate has increased traffic into the 
united states from canada 
when i95 first opened two miles from the mainenew brunswick 
border 4900 people a month entered the united states by 1987 
273000 people and 5000 trucks a month were streaming into the 
country according to marc russell us immigration and 
naturalization service supervisor at the border checkpoint 
the interstate which cost 140 million to build from bangor to 
houlton also created a new business district forcing motels 
restaurants and stores from downtown houlton or route 2a to close 
or move near the highway to accommodate the rerouted traffic 
some believe business has increased in houlton where the 
economy is based on the potato industry and the lumber trade 
there seems to be more activity in houlton than there has been 
in prior years said anderson an insurance and real estate 
agent maybe thats just a gut feeling but there seems to be 
more construction i think development around an interstate seems 
to snowball 
while the road has made access to southern maine easier life in 
houlton as one resident says hasnt changed much 
its just a long way from the rest of the world mrs ward 
said even though you can get to bangor in just under two hours 
you still have a long way to go if you want to go to boston 
</TEXT>
