<TEXT>
once called the hermit kingdom south 
korea is preparing to entertain the world at the 1988 olympic games 
and show just how much things have changed 
the country which for centuries tried to seal itself off from 
the world has been transformed in recent years into one of asias 
most modern and fastestgrowing nations staging the olympics is 
the crowning glory of south koreas economic rise 
seoul a sprawling city of 10 million people has been preparing 
for years to host the games and ensure that everything is right 
when the olympic spotlight turns on south korea beginning sept 17 
the city of highrise buildings broad avenues and meticulous 
neatness is dotted with olympic flags and banners for the games 
the five interlocked circles symbol of the olympic movement is 
stamped on everything from milk cartons and television logos to 
carriages in the seoul subway system 
the no 1 games the no 1 people proclaim the subway signs 
on every carriage door 
counters ticking off the days to the start of the games stand 
outside all government offices and police stations in every subway 
station and in many shops and businesses some buildings even have 
little counters in the elevators 
newspapers are filled with articles on the olympics seoul taxi 
drivers are taking courses in english and other foreign languages 
homeowners are being urged to provide accommodation for tourists 
and hotels and new shops are under construction all over seoul 
the sprawling olympic park in the south of seoul with its giant 
stadiums tracks and pools is ready for the games workers scurry 
around the immaculate complex every day polishing the stadiums and 
trimming lawns and trees 
but visitors hoping to attend the olympic games had better 
already have firm hotel and airline reservations accommodation is 
likely to be scarce with more than 200000 visitors expected 
visitors who want to get the real flavor of korea should get off 
the main streeets and take a walk through the sidestreets and 
alleys that are usually just one block over street life in seoul 
is colorful and entertaining 
little shops offer brightly colored quilts and basketwork 
antique dealers sell old pottery and elaborate korean chests stall 
holders are everywhere selling fruit vegetables and flowers 
sidewalk vendors or little makeshift restraurants offer onion 
pancakes rice noodles in red pepper sauce and jam and almond paste 
cakes roast chestnuts and dried squid 
koreans like to socialize over food and drink and seoul is 
covered with thousands of restaurants beer halls tea rooms snack 
counters and sidewalk vendors serving a vast range of dishes 
korean food offers distinctive spicy dishes such as pulgogi a 
barbecued beef that is cooked at your table and kalbi or barbecued 
beef ribs kimchi fiery pickled cabbage that is the most famous 
dish in korean cuisine accompanies just about every meal 
another pleasure are the many small and inexpensive noodle and 
rice restaurants where a steaming bowl of fish or beef soup can be 
had with noodles or rice for 2 or 3 
many visitors enjoy sampling both local brews and korean society 
by visiting korean beerhalls where local beers and a potent 
sorghum liquor called soju are served koreans love to sing and 
strangers and friends join in everything from country and western 
hits to haunting korean love melodies 
seoul has much to offer shoppers with bargains in clothes 
luggage shoes and leather goods porcelain oriental prints 
fabric and inexpensive jewelery several fur companies offer 
bargain fur coats that shoppers pick up at the airport on their way 
out 
the city is covered with shops department stores arcades and 
markets many visitors head for the itaewon district where english 
is widely spoken 
more colorful are the vast open air markets at tongdaemun and 
namdaemun where vendors sell everything from sneakers and bolts of 
brilliantly colored silk to live carp and turtles for dinner 
foreign visitors invariably say language is the biggest problem 
they encounter english and other foreign languages are not widely 
spoken but koreans will happily assist guests and smiles nods and 
hand gestures are often sufficient 
one problem confronting olympic visitors will be very strict 
security that could make getting around difficult at times during 
the games 
the government concerned about possible terrorist threats from 
rival communist north korea will deploy tens of thousands of 
troops and police to ensure the safety of the games and the 
visitors 
