monday it was delaying by two months the effective date of a rule 
designed to make it easier for investors to shop for mutual funds 
the commission said mutual funds can wait until july 1 before 
they must calculate yield in a standardized way so that consumers 
can readily compare the track records of competing funds 
when the commission decided on the new rule in january it set 
may 1 as the effective date however the investment company 
institute a trade group for mutual funds said its members needed 
more time to adjust their computer and accounting systems 
the sec in response has decided to allow funds to advertise 
their yield using the old methods of calculation through the end of 
june however the funds will have to disclose in the ads that the 
yield is not computed according to sec standards 
